. . .


First weve selected only numeric columns for the calculations since using the categorical data in a linear regression model is not suitable.
Then weve removed the Id column from data since it is a dummy attribute and doesnt relate to our model.
Then weve calculated pairwire correlation beased on complete observation pairs in dataset and created the correlation matrix.

We are only interested in correlations with SalePrice, so weve selected the 10 most correlated variables with the SalePrice excluding itself (correlation of an RV with itself is 1).
This data will become useful in the following questions.


After that weve visualized correlation matrix in three ways. first is a heatmap visualization. second is another vaiant of heatmap and the third is second visualization augmented with the results of meaningfullness test.
The confidence level for the conducted test is 95% and the significance level os 2e-16.

. . .


Weve developed this model using linear regression and the 10 variables weve just found.
By looking at models summary we can infer that we cannot reject the null hypothesis that some of the variables in the model are effective. so some of them including GarageArea, TotRmsAbvGrd and FullBath may not play a considerable role in our model.
The models degree of freedom is 1449 and has a relatively high adjusted R^2 value. showing that The linear modeling probably is not a bad choice.
The high F Statistics of the model on a relatively large number of data indicates that the hypothesis of all the parameters being zero (except intercept) is rejected.

. . normality, independance, Constant Variance .


In this question weve improved our model based on the given factors.
In the question 7 weve seen that the constant error variance assumption across all data range is not quiet right.
The linear regression model needs this assumption to hold in order to provide accurate results.
So weve used a logarithemic transformation and moved the data and model values in the log scales.
This way the amount of variance and change in the data will be controlled and the model will be more accurate.
The final model results will be exponented to get the price predictins.
The prediction and residual diagrams vs real values indicate that our model is far more accurate now.


Then we checked our model for multicollinearity with variance inflatin favtors test.
The small resulting values (smaller than 10 or 5) indicate that probably no multicollinearity and therefore no dependencies are present.


At last weve test our models distribution against a a t student distribution with the same degree of freedom.
In order to visualize the test results weve used QQ Plot from the car library.

The plot shows that our model is nearly normal in all the t quantiles except for first leftside quantiles where it has more rising slope than the t distribution.

. .


Weve compared the model variables agains one another in order to observe curve similarities to non linear functions.

It looks likely that TotalBsmtSF vs SalePrice is a sqrt-like function and GrLivArea vs SalePrice is a log-like function.
We think there is no more obvios non linearity evidences.

Then Weve recreated the mlodel and used this non linear relations instead:

[q9_lm <- lm(SalePriceLog ~ OverallQual + I(log(GrLivArea)) + GarageCars + YearRemodAdd + YearBuilt + I(sqrt(TotalBsmtSF)), q7_data)]

The final result is better than the previous model and can cover data variance better.
Average error absolute value is 3000 dollars and the variance is 39000 dollars.
